Who else’s cats just always want to be outside? People always seem surprised at the novelty of a cat on a leash but it’s the only way that we can take Oliver and Hank out with the pet leash policy. A couple tips if you haven’t tried to leash your cat or if you’ve tried and failed before.
1. Get a harness for your cat and put it on them in the house. They will flop over, walk strange and crouch for a while until they get used to it. It make take a while but try it for a few minutes a day until they relax. 
2. It isn’t exactly like walking a dog that goes where you lead. The cat is most likely going to be walking you on a leash rather than the other way around. Cats going to go where cat wants, just enjoy it. 
Any other tips for those that have been successful that you can think of? Comment below. 
#catonleash #cats #ragdoll #ragdollcat #catsofinstagram

Bald Faced Hornets are excellent pest control around the garden and despite being related to widely hated Yellow Jackets Wasp will readily kill them. Some of their hobbies include invoking fear in humans, pollinating flowers and and devouring the pears on my tree.

As a general rule, the fuzzier the caterpillar the more poisonous it is. Don’t touch the fuzzy ones. We found this one on our couch, it must have hitchhiked in on our clothes so I took it out and put it on this oak leaf. It is a White Tussock Moth and looks pretty unremarkable as a moth but as a caterpillar it looks like the alien scorpion of your nightmares.

A few images from this week from Minnesota, Michigan and Wisconsin.
Every year it seems like all the photographers head to Colorado for fall color. I always appreciate the solitude that leaves in Utah. Sadly this year I won’t be there to enjoy it.

We noticed these trees on a walk shortly after moving to Minnesota this year and were immediately excited to shoot them in the fall. They did not disappoint. Having them within walking distance from home makes them even cooler, at least to me.
With the winter approaching quickly in Minnesota I’m missing Utah a bit so here’s a photo of Utah.

This was my last good adventure before moving away from Utah. As the snow falls in Minnesota I am missing the desert a little and thinking of this unbelievably amazing view. Thanks you @nickolasawarner and @john.haymore and @anchorlyss for making this an unforgettable experience.

The adventure is sometimes the only reward which is enough on its own. Sometimes though, sometimes the reward is incredibly epic, rarely seen views experienced in complete solitude and a photo to share.
It’s beautiful UP here!

Muskegs are North American swamp or bogs consisting of a mixture of water and partly dead vegetation, frequently covered by a layer of sphagnum or other mosses. Besides being excellent carbon sinks are also pretty cool looking. Emily and I really enjoyed hunting for these photogenic bogs.

I’ve never seen anything like this growing up in the Southwest. Emily saw something that looked interesting on google earth and when we got the drone in the air to investigate we found this floating bog of moss and huge larch trees encircled in limitless autumn forest.

social_posts.post_text: Merry Christmas! There has been a lot of changes this year for us. A new state, house and job changes were easier to adjust to than expected and we have really been loving our new life here in Minnesota. The people have been really welcoming. Moving from Utah to Minnesota we were warned of the unbearably cold winters but here we are on Christmas Day enjoying a light rain and 50 degree temps so it seems even the weather has been really welcoming.

Tradition is just peer pressure from dead people 
John 13:34
MN-UT
